<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-65-0204 </DOCNO><TEXT>The Western alliance in the South Pacific has experienced three decadesof success based on a cooperative spirit established through its keystone,the ANZUS Treaty. Over the last few years some events have occurred inthe region which are now challenging this spirit. The author examinesthe alliance, including its history, objectives and the issues confrontingit. He also analyses current policies of ANZUS nations and their perceptionsof the Treaty. He concludes that the traditional ANZUS Treaty can nolonger meet the security objectives of its members, and requires majorrevision. A blueprint for change is suggested.</TEXT></DOC>